# <%= @project_name %>

Scaffolded <%= Atom.to_string(@runtime_class) %> connector package generated from the
workspace root.

## Runtime And Auth Posture

- runtime family: `<%= @runtime_class_literal %>`
- public auth binding is `connection_id`
- deterministic execution still uses short-lived credential leases published by
  the connector contract
<%= if @include_runtime_metadata do %>- authored non-direct routing is published through `runtime.driver: "<%= @runtime_driver_id %>"` on the manifest instead of an implicit runtime default
<% else %>- this direct scaffold keeps runtime routing inside the package handler and does not publish Harness driver metadata
<% end %>

## Scaffold Output

This package starts with:

- one authored manifest contract built from `AuthSpec`, `CatalogSpec`, and `OperationSpec`
- one derived executable capability projected from that authored operation
- a runtime-class-appropriate handler skeleton
- a deterministic conformance companion module
- package-local tests that prove the scaffold passes the baseline conformance flow
<%= if @include_runtime_metadata do %>
- a package-local `runtime_drivers/0` proof hook plus deterministic Harness
  driver in `lib/` so downstream package tests can load the same conformance surface

This scaffold already publishes the selected Harness runtime driver
`<%= @runtime_driver_id %>` on the authored contract. It does not invent a
legacy bridge default. The generated non-direct capability intentionally stays
`consumer_surface.mode: :connector_local` until you author a real shared
common surface and canonical `metadata.runtime_family`.
<% end %>

## What You Must Author

The scaffold is intentionally honest and minimal. It is the starting contract,
not the finished connector package. Replace these placeholders as you turn it
into a real connector:

Keep provider inventory, parity catalogs, and long-tail SDK helpers
connector-local unless you explicitly publish them through the manifest.
Target descriptors advertise compatibility and location only. They do not
override authored runtime.driver, runtime.provider, or runtime.options.

1. auth, catalog, operation ids, schemas, scopes, and policy metadata in `[<%= @module_file %>]`
2. handler logic in `[<%= @handler_file %>]`
3. deterministic fixture expectations in `[<%= @conformance_file %>]`
<%= if @include_test_support do %>4. deterministic Harness runtime behavior in `[<%= @conformance_harness_driver_file %>]`
<% end %>
5. this package `README.md` so it states the runtime family, auth posture,
   package-local verification commands, and live-proof status

## Proof Code Homes

Keep deterministic fixtures, companion modules, examples, scripts, and live
acceptance inside this package. Do not move connector proof code into the
workspace root.

Hosted webhook routing, async handlers, and app composition belong above the
connector package when that behavior is not part of the connector contract
itself.

## Package Verification

From the package root:

```bash
mix deps.get
mix compile --warnings-as-errors
mix test
mix docs
```

From the workspace root:

```bash
mix jido.conformance <%= @connector_module %>
mix ci
```

## Live Proof Status

No live proof is generated by default. Add package-local live acceptance only
when the real connector contract needs it, and keep that proof opt-in.

## Package Boundary

Do not widen this scaffold into root-level examples, provider code generation,
or app-only routing surfaces. Keep the connector package reviewable as an
isolated deliverable.
